
## Frappe/ERPNext Development Conventions

### Test-Driven Development (Frappe)
- Use `FrappeTestCase` as base class (provides DB rollback isolation)
- Test files: `test_{doctype_name}.py` alongside the DocType
- Run all: `bench --site {site} run-tests --app {app}`
- Run single: `bench --site {site} run-tests --doctype {DocType}`
- Run module: `bench --site {site} run-tests --module {dotted.module.path}`
- Always verify the test fails first before implementing — if it passes immediately, the test is wrong

### ERPNext Skills Workflow
- When receiving vague ERPNext requirements, use `erpnext-code-interpreter` skill to generate concrete technical specs
- The interpreter automatically maps to specific implementation skills (syntax-*, impl-*, errors-*, etc.)

### Frappe Logging Patterns
```python
# Errors (feeds Error Log doctype)
frappe.log_error(title="Short Title", message=f"Context: {relevant_vars}")

# Non-error logging (structured)
logger = frappe.logger("{app_name}", allow_site=True)
logger.info(f"[{doctype}] {action}: {context}")
logger.debug(f"[{doctype}] Payload: {json.dumps(data, indent=2)}")
logger.warning(f"[{doctype}] Unexpected state: {description}")
```

### bench migrate Conventions
- Always commit code before running bench migrate
- Always backup before migrate: `bench --site {site} backup`
- Consider spawning migration-checker agent for non-trivial schema changes
- After migrate, check for fixture drift and export if needed

### Default PR Target
- Default PR target for Frappe projects: `development` branch
- Never target `main`, `master`, or `version-15` without explicit instruction

### frappe.throw vs raise
- `frappe.throw()` for user-facing validation errors (shows red banner, rolls back)
- `raise` for programming errors (bugs that should never reach users)
- Always use `_()` for translatable error messages

### Document Lifecycle Rules
- NEVER call `frappe.db` inside `validate` — defer DB operations to `on_update`
- Check `self.flags.ignore_validate` before expensive validation
- Check `self.flags.in_import` to skip notifications during data import
- Use `frappe.enqueue` for long-running tasks in `on_submit`
